Module 1 & 2: Hardware and its Components
1)What is an input device?
=>An input device sends data or instructions from the user into the computer. Examples: keyboard, mouse, scanner, microphone.
2)What are output devices?
=>Output devices display or present processed data from the computer to the user. Examples: monitor/display, printer, speakers/headphones, projector.
3)What is CPU?
=>The CPU (Central Processing Unit) is the "brain" of the computer. It performs calculations, executes instructions from programs, and controls other hardware components.
4)What are the types of CPU?
=>By manufacturer: Intel (e.g., Core i3/i5/i7/i9) and AMD (e.g., Ryzen series).
  By architecture: Desktop CPUs, mobile/laptop CPUs, server CPUs.
  Older classifications: Single-core, dual-core, quad-core, multi-core
5)What do we need to keep the CPU healthy?
=>Proper cooling (heatsink + fan or liquid cooler).
o	High-quality thermal paste between CPU and heatsink.
o	Clean dust from fans/heatsink regularly (every 3–6 months).
o	Good airflow in the PC case.
o	Stable power supply (avoid voltage fluctuations).
o	Monitor temperatures with software; reapply thermal paste every 1–3 years.
o	Avoid overclocking without proper cooling.
6)Practical: Remove processor, apply thermal paste, and reinstall
==>
i)Power off, unplug, and ground yourself (anti-static wrist strap).
ii)Open case, disconnect CPU fan power.
iii)Release socket lever, lift heatsink/fan carefully.
iv)Gently lift CPU out of socket.
v)Clean old thermal paste from CPU and heatsink with isopropyl alcohol and lint-free cloth.
vi)Apply pea-sized dot of new thermal paste to center of CPU.
vii)Reinsert CPU (align triangle/notch), lower lever to lock.
viii)Reattach heatsink/fan, reconnect power.
ix)Close case and test boot.

7)Practical: Identify CPU and its sockets
=>Look at the CPU (usually under the heatsink): Check markings (e.g., Intel Core i5-12400 or AMD Ryzen 5).
Socket types: LGA (Land Grid Array – pins on motherboard), PGA (Pin Grid Array – pins on CPU, or BGA.
8)What is memory?
=>Memory (primarily RAM) is temporary storage that holds data and instructions the CPU is actively using. It allows fast read/write access for running programs.

9)What are the types of memory?
=>
Primary memory: RAM (volatile – loses data when powered off) and ROM (non-volatile – retains data).
RAM subtypes: DRAM (main system memory), SRAM (faster, used in cache).
ROM subtypes: PROM, EPROM, EEPROM (used for firmware like BIOS).
Secondary memory: HDD, SSD, USB drives, optical discs (non-volatile, for long-term storage).
Cache memory

