13)What is bios?
BIOS (Basic Input/Output System) is firmware stored on a chip on the motherboard. It initializes hardware during boot, performs POST (Power-On Self-Test), and loads the OS.

14)Describe working process of BIOS. 
=> Power on → BIOS runs POST (checks CPU, RAM, storage, etc.).
   Initializes hardware (keyboard, display, drives).
   Looks for bootable device (per boot order).
   Loads bootloader → hands control to OS.
   
15)Do a practical of Hard resetting the BIOS.
=> Press Delete/F12 while powering on.
   Select Load Setup Defaults before exiting.

16)Practical: Identifying BIOS chip from the motherboard
=> Look for a rectangular or square chip labeled with "BIOS", "UEFI", or manufacturer name.
   It's usually near the battery or edge of the board.
   
17)What is CMOS?
=> CMOS (Complementary Metal-Oxide-Semiconductor) is a small battery-powered memory chip that stores BIOS/UEFI settings (date/time, boot order, hardware config). It loses data without the battery.


18)What is motherboard?
=>The motherboard is the main circuit board that connects all hardware components (CPU,         
  RAM, storage, expansion cards, etc.) and allows them to communicate.

19)Describe types of motherboard
=> PC-Tx: used in old traditional CPUs
   AT: advanced technology
   ATX: advanced technology extended(Types: Standard, pico, nano, etc)
   ITX: Information Technology Extended
   BTX: Balanced Technology Extended 

20)Practical: Identifying parts of motherboard
=>CPU socket, RAM (DIMM) slots, PCIe slots (for GPU), SATA ports (storage), chipset            
  (Northbridge/Southbridge or integrated), I/O ports (USB, HDMI), power connectors (24-pin  
  ATX, 8-pin CPU), BIOS chip, CMOS battery, front panel connectors.

21)Do a practical by removing all removable parts from the motherboard.
=>Power off/unplug. Remove: CPU + cooler, RAM sticks, GPU/expansion cards, storage drives (SATA/M.2), all cables (power, data), CMOS, processor.

22)What is system bus?
  The system bus (or front-side bus in older systems) is the communication pathway between      
  CPU, memory, and other components. It includes address, data, and control buses.

23)What is chipset and types of chipset?
=>The chipset is a set of chips managing data flow on the motherboard. Traditional types:
  Northbridge — Handles high-speed communication (CPU to RAM, GPU).
  Southbridge — Handles lower-speed I/O (USB, storage, audio, BIOS).
  Modern chipsets are often integrated into a single chip

